      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "SQA documentation demonstrates version control, regression testing, and documented build procedures consistent with MRL 2 requirements.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2021R2 is a commercially validated solver with documented SQA processes. Release notes and regression test reports were reviewed and confirm compliance with MRL 2 SQA requirements. Version control of case files maintained via institutional repository."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification evidence from published benchmark solutions or vendor documentation demonstrating correct implementation of governing equations for incompressible viscous flow.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent has been extensively verified against standard CFD benchmarks (lid-driven cavity, Poiseuille flow, backward-facing step) as documented in the vendor verification and validation manual. Published literature corroborates solver accuracy for rotodynamic pump simulations at the Reynolds number range of interest."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence study using at least three systematically refined meshes; GCI reported for primary QoI (NIH) at the nominal operating point.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study (coarse: 4.2M cells, medium: 11.7M cells, fine: 31.4M cells) was performed at the 5 L/min, 3000 RPM operating point. Grid Convergence Index for NIH was 3.8% (medium-to-fine), falling below the 5% threshold. The medium mesh was selected for the parametric sweep, exceeding the MRL 2 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (fluid properties, rotational speed, flow rate, temperature) are documented with measurement uncertainty and match the simulated boundary conditions within acceptable tolerances.",
      "rationale": "FDA bench test data used for validation employed bovine blood analog (glycerol-water, matched viscosity) at 37°C. Flow rate controlled to ±0.05 L/min, rotational speed to ±10 RPM. Boundary conditions in the CFD model were set to match reported experimental values. Fluid property uncertainty propagation documented in the validation report."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., E% or validation uncertainty U_val) computed for NIH across all validation operating points; metric within acceptance band.",
      "rationale": "NIH predictions compared against experimental measurements at 6 operating points spanning 3–6 L/min and 2500–3500 RPM. Mean absolute percentage error of 11.4% observed, within the pre-specified 15% acceptance threshold. Validation uncertainty U_val computed per ASME V&V 20 methodology and reported as 18.2% of mean experimental NIH."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoIs used in validation (NIH, shear stress distribution) are directly relevant to the decision question of identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for CPB use.",
      "rationale": "Normalized Index of Hemolysis is the regulatory-accepted metric for blood damage assessment in CPB devices and directly maps to the decision question. Shear stress magnitude and exposure time distributions, from which NIH is derived, are the mechanistic QoIs. Both are directly relevant to worst-case operating point identification."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments were conducted on the same device geometry (FDA generic centrifugal pump) under operating conditions spanning the intended CPB use envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation data were collected on the FDA generic centrifugal pump benchmark geometry — identical to the simulated geometry. Operating conditions cover the CPB clinical range (3–6 L/min, 2000–4000 RPM). The validation domain is assessed as representative of the intended use envelope, supporting extrapolation to worst-case identification within this range."
    },
    {
